{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Sherlock Holmes and the Shadwell Shadows | title_orig = | translator = | image = Sherlock Holmes and the Shadwell Shadows.jpg | caption = | author = [[James Lovegrove]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | genre = [[Mystery novels]] | publisher = [[Titan Books]] | release_date = 2016 | media_type = Print (hardback & paperback) | pages = | isbn = 9781783295937 | isbn_note = (first U.S. edition, hardback) | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = [[Sherlock Holmes and the Miskatonic Monstrosities]] }}
'''''Sherlock Holmes and the Shadwell Shadows''''' is a [[mystery novel]] by [[James Lovegrove]]. It is a [[Sherlock Holmes pastiches|Sherlock Holmes pastiche]] that involves [[H. P. Lovecraft]]'s [[Cthulhu Mythos]].<ref name="starburst">{{cite web|title=The Cthulhu Casebooks – Sherlock Holmes and the Shadwell Shadows|url=https://www.starburstmagazine.com/reviews/sherlock-holmes-shadwell-shadows-review|work=[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]|date=|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> It is the first book in a planned trilogy of ''[[James Lovegrove#The Cthulhu Casebooks|The Cthulhu Casebooks]]'' with the second novel, ''[[Sherlock Holmes and the Miskatonic Monstrosities]]'', having been released in November 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Sherlock Holmes and the Miskatonic Monstrosities|url=https://titanbooks.com/the-cthulhu-casebooks-sherlock-holmes-and-the-miskatonic-monstrosities-8100/|work=[[Titan Books]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> and the third, ''Sherlock Holmes and the Sussex Sea-Devils'', in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Eric|title=The best recent science fiction, fantasy and horror – reviews roundup |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/nov/09/the-best-recent-science-fiction-fantasy-and-horror-reviews-roundup|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=November 9, 2018|accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>
==Plot== A series of mysterious deaths inspire [[Sherlock Holmes]] and [[Dr. Watson]] to investigate the criminal element of the [[East End of London]]. Their investigation leads to crime lord Gong-Fen Shou but further opens their eyes to the existence of something [[Cthulhu Mythos deities|much worse]].
==Reception== Reviewers have praised Lovegrove's use of Doyle's characters within a [[Lovecraftian horror|Lovecraftian]] conceit. Glenn Dallas of ''[[Seattle Book Review]]'' said "Lovegrove does an outstanding job of evoking Doyle’s style and mixing in healthy dollops of the macabre and fantastic that define the Cthulhu Mythos."<ref>{{cite web|last=Dallas|first=Glenn|title=The Cthulhu Casebooks – Sherlock Holmes and the Shadwell Shadows|url=https://seattlebookreview.com/product/the-cthulhu-casebooks-sherlock-holmes-and-the-shadwell-shadows/|work=[[Seattle Book Review]]|date=|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' said of the novel, "The pastiche is pitch-perfect; Lovegrove tells a thrilling tale and vividly renders the atmosphere of Victorian London."<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Eric|title=The best recent science fiction, fantasy and horror novels – reviews roundup |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/feb/03/the-best-recent-science-fiction-fantasy-and-horror-novels-reviews-roundup|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 3, 2017|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Starburst (magazine)|Starburst]]'' magazine said of the book "It retains the spirit of classic Holmes, while the integration of Lovecraft mythos is handled with careful aplomb."<ref name="starburst"/> Bob Byrne for ''[[Black Gate (magazine)|Black Gate]]'' said "If you like your Holmes with some horror: or if you like Cthulhu tales, I think you are going to like this book."<ref name="blackgate">{{cite web|last=Byrne|first=Bob|title=The Public Life of Sherlock Holmes: Cthulhu Casebooks & Nightmares|url=https://www.blackgate.com/2016/12/26/the-public-life-of-sherlock-holmes-cthulhu-casebooks-nightmares/|work=[[Black Gate (magazine)|Black Gate]]|date=December 26, 2016|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Byrne particularly liked that Lovegrove showed a "unpolished Holmes" early in his career.<ref name="blackgate"/>
